    "recap_url": "https://www.12thman.com/news/2026/3/22/offense-explodes-no-23-baseball-salvages-series-finale-with-no-7-georgia-18-5",
    "recap_headline": "Texas A&M",
    "recap_text": "BRYAN-COLLEGE STATION\u00a0\u2013\nNo. 23 Texas A&M saw the bats come alive Sunday afternoon from Olsen Field at Blue Bell Park, claiming the series finale in seven innings over No. 7 Georgia, 18-5.\nThe Maroon & White (18-5, 2-4) scored in each offensive frame and 10 Aggies recorded a hit. As a unit, the Texas A&M totaled 18 runs on 16 hits and 11 walks. Four batters registered multi-hit performances and five logged multiple RBI.\nNico Partida\npowered the offense with a career day at the dish, notching four hits and six RBI. The Manvel, Texas, native led off the second inning with a double off the wall in right field and drove in a run in the third with a single up the middle. His first career grand slam in the fourth inning put the Aggies up, 10-1. The rookie charted his sixth RBI of the game in the fifth inning with a sharp single to left field.\nGavin Grahovac\nand\nBear Harrison\neach tallied multiple hits and drove in two RBI. Harrison reached base four times in the win, including a single, a double and a pair of walks.\nJake Duer\nplated three runs, with two coming on a double down the left field line in the fifth.\nChris Hacopian\n,\nCaden Sorrell\nand Partida each touched home plate three times to add the Aggies' total.\nBoston Kellner\nreached base in each plate appearance, logging a single and a career-high four walks.\nAiden Sims\n(4-0) earned his first career conference win, dealing 5.2 innings while suffering three earned runs on just two hits and one walk. The righty punched out eight batters, with seven coming in the first four frames.\nClayton Freshcorn\ntossed the last 1.1 innings, allowing two runs on two hits with one strikeout.\nTOP PLAYERS\nNico Partida\n\u2013 4-for-4, 3 R, 6 RBI, 1 2B, 1 HR\nBear Harrison\n\u2013 2-for-3, 1 R, 2 RBI, 1 2B, 2 BB\nGavin Grahovac\n\u2013 2-for-5, 1 R, 2 RBI\nCaden Sorrell\n\u2013 1-for-2, 3 R, 3 BB\nChris Hacopian\n\u2013 2-for-3, 3 R, 1 BB\nJake Duer\n- 1-for-3, 3 R, 3 RBI, 1 2B, 1 BB\nBoston Kellner\n\u2013 1-for-1, 1 R, 1 RBI, 4 BB\nAiden Sims\n\u2013 W (4-0), 5.2 IP, 2 H, 3 ER, 1 BB, 8 K\nSCORING SUMMARY\nB1 | Sorrell walked and advanced to second on a wild pitch. Hacopian floated a single over the second baseman to move Sorrell to third. Duer plated a run on a groundout to third base, moving Hacopian to second.\nBlake Binderup\nbrought another run home on a line-drive single to left field. A&M 2, UGA 0.\nT2 | Jordy Oriach knocked a solo homer to right-center field. A&M 2, UGA 1.\nB2 |Partida led off with a double to deep right-center field. Harrison singled to right field, moving Partida to third. Kellner walked to load the bases and Grahovac plated a run on a fielder's choice out to the shortstop. A&M 3, UGA 1.\nB3 | Hacopian ripped a single through the right side but was put out on a Duer fielder's choice. Binderup was hit by a pitch to move Duer to into scoring position. Partida followed with a single up the middle, scoring Duer and moving Binderup to third. Partida advanced to second on the throw. Harrison mashed a double to center field to plate both runners. A&M 6, UGA 1.\nB4 | Sorrell reached on an infield single, followed by consecutive walks from Hacopian and Duer. Partida cleared the bases with an opposite-field grand slam. A&M 10, UGA 1.\nB5 | Kellner led off with a single to left field. Grahovac singled through the left side and Sorrell walked to load the bases. Kellner scored on an errant throw by the first baseman on a ground ball off the bat of Hacopian. Duer shot a double down the left field line to plate two runs. Binderup brought a run home on a sacrifice fly to center field. With a runner on third, Partida drove in his sixth RBI of the contest on a single to left field.\nTerrence Kiel II\nreached on a fielder's choice that put out Partida. Harrison and Kellner walked to load the bases once again. All runners advanced on a wild pitch, with Kiel scoring a run. Grahovac singled in the infield to plate the seventh run of the frame. A&M 17, UGA 1.\nT6 | Jack Arcamone walked and Rylan Lujo was hit by a pitch. Ty Peeples drove a double to right-center field to plate a pair of runs. A&M 17, UGA 3.\nB6 | Wilson drove the first pitch of the frame to right field for a double. Farr reach on an infield single, but Wilson stayed put at second. LaBuda reached on an uncanny 5-4-5 fielder's choice that put Wilson out at third. Harrison walked, and Kellner walked with the bases load to bring a run home. A&M 18, UGA 3.\nT7| Arcamone doubled to the right-center gap and Lujo homered to left-center. A&M 18, UGA 5.\nGAME NOTES\nSunday's contest marked the 29th meeting all-time between the clubs. With the win, the Aggies extend their lead in the series to 17-12.\nBlue Bell Park held 6,087 fans Sunday afternoon. Over the weekend, the park held 20,882 fans, marking the sixth-largest crowd for a three-game series all-time and the fifth-most since the renovations in 2012.\nThe 18 runs scored are the most in a conference game by the Maroon & White since April 27, 2024 (19 vs. Georgia)\nPartida logged a career-best four hits and six RBI.\nKellner walked four times, becoming the first Aggie to accomplish the feat since\nJace LaViolette\non May 18, 2023.\nThe freshman has reached base safely in all 23 games this season.\nKiel's on-base streak ended at 22 games.\nGrahovac and Sorrell extended their respective on-base streaks to 17 games.\nSorrell matched a career high with three walks.\nDuer and Hacopian each scored a season-high three runs.\n18 Aggies made appearances in the win.\nUP NEXT\nTexas A&M concludes its five-game homestand with midweek action against HCU. First pitch on Tuesday is slated for 6 p.m. from Olsen Field at Blue Bell Park.\nFollow the Aggies\nVisit for more information on Texas A&M baseball. Fans can keep up to date with the A&M baseball team on\u00a0Facebook, Instagram\u00a0and X by following @aggiebaseball.",
